<div id="review_2491590755" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2491590755" />
    <a title="Eric Allen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6229358-eric-allen"><img alt="Eric Allen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1560117879p2/6229358.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2491590755?book_show_action=true">Aug 12, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eric Allen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eric Allen" href="/user/show/6229358-eric-allen">Eric Allen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2491590755" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8997388129537359205">So, Foundation and Empire did something a little different from the first book. It still had a little bit at the beginning about another crisis that the Foundation had to get through, but then it moves into throwing a wrench into the works. The plan to found the second empire within 1000 years is thrown off by the introduction of the Mule, a single man with the power to control the emotions of others and inspire absolute devotion in them sets out to conquer the Foundation and found his own new e</span>
  <span id="freeText8997388129537359205" style="display:none">So, Foundation and Empire did something a little different from the first book. It still had a little bit at the beginning about another crisis that the Foundation had to get through, but then it moves into throwing a wrench into the works. The plan to found the second empire within 1000 years is thrown off by the introduction of the Mule, a single man with the power to control the emotions of others and inspire absolute devotion in them sets out to conquer the Foundation and found his own new empire in its place. The Mule was unforeseen in the plan, and so it comes down to the last few people no under the Mule's control to thwart his plans, and seek out the Second Foundation to save the Foundation and the plan.<br /><br />Two things that the first book lacked were any real characters, and an antagonist. The nature of the story didn't really require either. But here, instead of doing more of the same, Asimov tricks you out by making it look like he's going to continue with the same formula, and then strays about as far from it as he possibly can, introducing protagonists and an antagonist, and a struggle between them over the location of the Second Foundation. I realize that this book was first published something like 65 years ago, but I really don't want to ruin the twist at the end for anyone that may not be familiar with the series, but it is pretty well pulled off. It's the right kind of twist, where you can look back at the book and see how everything in it points to the twist, but you never really notice it until it's revealed in the end.<br /><br />This book is just as good, maybe even a little better, than the first book. And I definitely recommend it, and the entire Foundation series for that matter, to any fans of sci-fi.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8997388129537359205" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


